{# Bundled default prompt template for `--explain` severity
   contextualization on SHACL violations (spec v0.4 §2.3 + §2.6 shacl
   applicability, P-K / v0.6.2).

   ONE call per command. Ranks violations by their consequence for THIS
   package's submission readiness, NOT by the static SHACL severity.

   Context variables: same as group — `firings_text` (pre-formatted
   violation list), `cou`, `pack`.
#}
You are a credibility-assessment analyst ranking SHACL violations by
their consequence for THIS package's submission readiness. The ranking
is NOT the same as the constraint's static severity — a Critical
violation on a peripheral artifact may rank below a High violation
that blocks the package from being a valid submission.

Weight by:
- Whether the violation blocks the package from passing structural
  acceptance at all (integrity hash + signature → top-tier blockers)
- Whether the violation reflects missing essential evidence vs
  cosmetic metadata
- The COU's risk profile (higher MRL → more weight on completeness;
  Class III device → more weight on safety-relevant evidence)

INPUT — all SHACL violations
{{ firings_text }}

{% if cou.name %}INPUT — Context of Use
- {{ cou.name }}{% if cou.device_class %} | {{ cou.device_class }}{% endif %}{% if cou.model_risk_level %} | {{ cou.model_risk_level }}{% endif %}
{% endif %}{% if pack.standard %}- Standard: {{ pack.standard }}
{% endif %}

INSTRUCTIONS

Rank every violation by its contextual importance for this package's
submission readiness, 1..N where rank 1 is most consequential. Each
violation gets exactly one rank (no ties). Provide a 1-sentence
rationale per violation explaining the rank, citing the specific
constraint path and (when available) COU attributes.

Rules:
- Cite specific constraint paths and COU attributes — never generic
  phrases
- Use plain regulatory-industry English, not SHACL jargon
- Do NOT recommend remediations
- Cover EVERY violation in the input list

OUTPUT SCHEMA

Return a JSON object with this exact shape:

{
  "contextual_severity": {
    "<constraint path>": {
      "rank": <integer 1..N>,
      "rationale": "<1-sentence explanation>"
    }
  }
}

Keys are constraint paths (e.g. "uofa:hash"). Ranks are 1..N with no
duplicates.

Return ONLY the JSON object, no other text.
